of that uninterrupted narrative.‹/p›‹p›Jameson applies his interpretive theory to nineteenth- and twentieth-century texts, including the works of Balzac, Gissing, and Conrad. Throughout, he considers other interpretive approaches to the works he discusses, assessing the importance and limitations of methods as different as Lacanian psychoanalysis, semiotics, dialectical analysis, and allegorical readings. The book as a whole raises directly issues that have been only implicit in Jameson's earlier work, namely the relationship between dialectics and structuralism, and the tension between the German and the French aesthetic traditions.‹/p›‹p›‹b›‹i›The Political Unconscious‹/i›‹/b› is a masterly introduction to both the method and the practice of Marxist criticism. Defining a mode of criticism and applying it successfully to individual works, it bridges the gap between theoretical speculation and textual analysis.‹/p›  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and literature. 0aCriticism. 0aFictionxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aFictionxHistory and criticism. 0aHermeneutics. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 4aLiterary Studies.  aadorno.  aalways historicise.  abooks about narratology.  abooks for literary scholars.  abooks on literary theory.  abooks on rhetoric.  acommunisim in literature.  acommunism and literature.  acritical theory in literature.  adialectical thought.  aenglish literature.  agenre criticism.  ahermeneutics.  ahistorical context in literature.  ahistoricise.  ahistory of theory.  ahow to read literature.  aintroduction to literary theory.  alinguistics.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary movements.  aliterary scholars.  aliterary studies.  aliterary theory.  aliterature symbology.  amagical narrative.  amarxist critic